<h2>Have We Learned Our Lessons?</h2>
<p>History whispers warnings: post-2008 bailouts taught fiscal prudence, yet 2025's rising debts risk repeats. Protectionism's double edge &mdash; short-term shielding vs. long-term stagnation &mdash; is evident in today's tariffs, which the UN notes foster complacency if prolonged. Progress is real: 97 million "markets of tomorrow" jobs by 2025 demand reskilling. But divergences persist. Without redoubled reforms, 2025 risks a "limping" recovery.</p>

<div class="verdict">Partial credit. We've adapted where incentives align &mdash; digital tools, green markets &mdash; but political polarization and short-termism hobble bolder action.</div>

<p>Estonia and Singapore shine as beacons: proof that learning from the past &mdash; embracing openness, iteration, and discipline &mdash; unlocks enduring growth. Germany, and the world, would do well to follow suit before the next shock arrives.</p>

